<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
  <chapter xml:id="ch-function-operators" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Function Operators</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        In this chapter, you'll learn about function operators. A
        <em>function operator</em> is a function that takes one (or more)
        functions as input and returns a function as output. The following code
        shows a simple function operator, <c>chatty()</c>. It wraps a function,
        making a new function that prints out its first argument. You might
        create a function like this because it gives you a window to see how
        functionals, like <c>map_int()</c>, work.
      </p>

      <program language="r">
        <input>
chatty &lt;- function(f) {
  force(f)
  
  function(x, ...) {
    res &lt;- f(x, ...)
    cat("Processing ", x, "\n", sep = "")
    res
  }
}
f &lt;- function(x) x ^ 2
s &lt;- c(3, 2, 1)

purrr::map_dbl(s, chatty(f))
#&gt; Processing 3
#&gt; Processing 2
#&gt; Processing 1
#&gt; [1] 9 4 1
        </input>
      </program>
    </introduction>

  </chapter>
